aws::graph::propositions: # Aviation Accident Report - Cessna 310 Landing Gear Failure in Tampa
The accident occurred in Tampa, Florida.
The accident occurred on August 21, 2019, at 12:35 Local time.
The aircraft involved was a Cessna 310.
The defining event was a system/component malfunction/failure (non-power).
The flight was conducted under Part 91: General aviation - Personal.
The accident number was ERA19LA255.
The aircraft registration was N2299F.
The aircraft sustained substantial damage.
There were no injuries to the sole occupant.
During the landing approach, the pilot noted that the right main landing gear would not extend into the down and locked position.
During touchdown, the right main landing gear began to collapse.
The pilot performed a go-around after the gear began to collapse.
The pilot climbed to altitude after the go-around.
The pilot attempted emergency procedures to extend the right main landing gear.
The pilot attempted g-loading maneuvers to extend the right main landing gear.
The pilot was unable to extend the right main landing gear into the down and locked position.
The pilot chose to land with the landing gear retracted.
Maintenance personnel were unable to extend and lock the right main landing gear during recovery of the airplane.
Maintenance personnel were able to extend and lock the nose gear into position.
Maintenance personnel were able to extend and lock the left main landing gear into position.
The right main landing gear was manually extended and braced.
The aircraft was towed to the ramp after the right main landing gear was manually extended and braced.
The pilot/operator reported that the damage to the aircraft was substantial.
A complete examination of the right main landing gear was not performed.
The reason for the right main landing gear anomaly could not be determined.
The National Transportation Safety Board determined the probable cause of this accident to be the failure of the right main landing gear to fully extend and lock.

text:
# Aviation Investigation Final Report

## Location:
Tampa, Florida

## Date & Time: 
August 21, 2019, 12:35 Local

## Aircraft:
Cessna 310

## Defining Event:
Sys/Comp malf/fail (non-power)

## Flight Conducted Under:
Part 91: General aviation - Personal

## Accident Number:
ERA19LA255

## Registration:
N2299F

## Aircraft Damage:
Substantial

## Injuries:
1 None

## Analysis

During the landing approach, the pilot noted that the right main landing gear would not extend into the down and locked position, and, during touchdown, the gear began to collapse. He performed a go-around, climbed to altitude, and attempted emergency procedures and g-loading maneuvers but was unable to extend the right main landing gear into the down and locked position. Ultimately, the pilot chose to land with the landing gear retracted. During recovery of the airplane from the runway, maintenance personnel were unable to extend and lock the right main landing gear, but they were able to extend and lock the nose and left main landing gears into position. The right main landing gear was manually extended and braced, then towed to the ramp. The pilot/operator of the aircraft reported that the damage to the aircraft was substantial.

A complete examination of the right main landing gear was not performed; therefore, the reason for the right main landing gear anomaly could not be determined.

## Probable Cause and Findings

The National Transportation Safety Board determines the probable cause(s) of this accident to be:

The failure of the right main landing gear to fully extend and lock for reasons that could not be determined.
